{"key":"processedPost-17187466","value":{"id":17187466,"first":17184345,"last":17187466,"when":1352437186,"utime":"11/09/12 06:59 AM","content":"I think emphasis on 'nutes' in mushroom growing is misguided.&nbsp; After all, straw has almost no nutes in the traditional sense, yet the biggest mushrooms I've ever grown were on straw.<br /><br />Adding vermiculite to any bulk substrate will make it perform better.&nbsp; Coir works well when applied as a casing layer or when spawned by grains as a bulk substrate.&nbsp; When it's used as a casing layer, a good argument could be made that it's simply a top layer of bulk substrate, but whatever it is, it works pretty well.<br /><br />Mold spores have a hard time germinating on coir for reasons still unknown, but that contaminant resistance makes it a great beginner substrate.&nbsp; Of course, if your spawn is contaminated you're still screwed, with or without coir.<br />RR","title":"Re: Instead of using Coir","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}